must be 28,000 times...

733
00:48:11,477 --> 00:48:15,777
...further away than the sun,
or about half a light-year away.

734
00:48:16,382 --> 00:48:19,146
It's hard to remember
just how bright a star is...

735
00:48:19,352 --> 00:48:23,186
...hours after you've looked at it,
but Huygens remembered very well.

736
00:48:23,389 --> 00:48:27,416
If he had known that Sirius was
intrinsically brighter than the sun...

737
00:48:27,626 --> 00:48:30,026
...he would've gotten
the answer exactly right.

738
00:48:30,229 --> 00:48:34,290
Sirius is 8.8 light-years
away from us.

739
00:48:35,267 --> 00:48:38,134
Between Aristarchus and Huygens...

740
00:48:38,337 --> 00:48:41,568
...people had answered that question
which had so excited me...

741
00:48:41,774 --> 00:48:43,639
...as a young boy growing up
in Brooklyn:

742
00:48:43,843 --> 00:48:46,209
The question, "What are the stars?"

743
00:48:49,648 --> 00:48:54,585
And the answer is that the stars are
mighty suns, light-years away...

744
00:48:54,787 --> 00:48:57,187
...in the depths
of interstellar space.

745
00:49:02,995 --> 00:49:07,329
And around those suns,
are there other planets?

746
00:49:08,401 --> 00:49:10,369
And on those other worlds...

747
00:49:10,569 --> 00:49:13,538
...are there beings
who wonder as we do?

748
00:49:17,910 --> 00:49:20,310
Here is a light bulb...

749
00:49:20,513 --> 00:49:23,073
...which is supposed to represent
a nearby star.

750
00:49:23,282 --> 00:49:26,740
Next to it, and very hard to see
because of the bright light...

751
00:49:26,952 --> 00:49:28,317
...is a planet.

752
00:49:28,521 --> 00:49:32,048
We'll need a volunteer.
Who would like to come up, please?

753
00:49:32,725 --> 00:49:35,319
Ordinarily, it's hard to
see the planet...

754
00:49:35,528 --> 00:49:39,487
...because it's so close that the star
washes out the planet.

755
00:49:39,698 --> 00:49:44,135
But if we're able to put something
in front of the star...

756
00:49:44,336 --> 00:49:47,863
...to make an artificial eclipse,
then we might be able to see the planet.

757
00:49:48,073 --> 00:49:52,339
I'm gonna stand over here.
Imagine that I'm a telescope...

758
00:49:52,545 --> 00:49:53,978
...somewhere near the Earth.

759
00:49:54,180 --> 00:49:58,082
And, Tab, if you'd slowly move
the disc across.

760
00:49:58,284 --> 00:50:00,275
Good. A little faster would be nice.

761
00:50:00,486 --> 00:50:03,114
Now you're just beginning to cover
over the star.

762
00:50:03,322 --> 00:50:06,348
I really can't see the planet at all.
Keep going.

763
00:50:06,559 --> 00:50:08,026
Now, right there...

764
00:50:08,227 --> 00:50:10,593
...I can't see the star at all...

765
00:50:10,796 --> 00:50:14,698
...and I see the planet lit
by the light of the star.

766
00:50:14,900 --> 00:50:18,233
Now, that is a method for looking
for planets...

767
00:50:18,437 --> 00:50:20,268
...around nearby stars.

768
00:50:20,473 --> 00:50:25,410
And that method uses a spacecraft
to hold the disc...

769
00:50:25,945 --> 00:50:28,413
...and scan the sky
for another telescope...

770
00:50:28,614 --> 00:50:31,344
...to see if there are any planets.

771
00:50:31,550 --> 00:50:35,884
Tab, you accomplished your mission
to look for planets around other stars.

772
00:50:36,088 --> 00:50:39,251
Thank you for being
our interplanetary spacecraft.

773
00:50:39,458 --> 00:50:42,052
So this is one way.

774
00:50:42,261 --> 00:50:45,662
And there are spaceships
that will be able to do this...

775
00:50:45,865 --> 00:50:47,628
...in the next 1 0 years or so.

776
00:50:47,833 --> 00:50:49,300
And there's another way.

777
00:50:49,502 --> 00:50:52,027
This has already been tried
from the Earth.

778
00:50:52,238 --> 00:50:56,334
Imagine that there's a nearby star
